{"TopicId":188650,"ForumId":44,"TopicTitle":"Fusion Driven Rocket","CreatedByName":"tater","CreatedById":119411,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-03T18:50:35Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"tater","CreatedById":119411,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-03T18:50:35Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/niac_2012_phaseii_slough_fusiondrivenrocketneclearpropulsiontagged.pdf\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003Ehttps://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/niac_2012_phaseii_slough_fusiondrivenrocketneclearpropulsiontagged.pdf\u003C/a\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\nQuote\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThe Fusion Driven rocket (FDR) represents a revolutionary approach to fusion propulsion where the power source releases its energy directly into the propellant, not requiring conversion to electricity. It employs a solid lithium propellant that requires no significant tankage mass. The propellant is rapidly heated and accelerated to high exhaust velocity (\u0026gt; 30 km/s), while having no substantial physical interaction with the spacecraft thereby avoiding damage to the rocket and limiting both the thermal heat load and radiator mass.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThis is pretty interesting.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nThey even propose a crew mission to Mars could be done with a \u003Cem\u003Esingle\u003C/em\u003E, 130 Mt to LEO launch. Spacecraft orbits Mars and returns to Earth orbit propulsively.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTMI burn is 7.6k/s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nMOI burn is 13.8 km/s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTEI is 16.2 km/s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nEOI is 11.8 km/s\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nTotal mission duration (including 30 day stay on martian surface) is 210 days.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsEmbeddedVideo\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 frameborder=\u00220\u0022 height=\u0022270\u0022 width=\u0022480\u0022 data-embed-src=\u0022https://www.youtube.com/embed/tHSOmOu61b0?feature=oembed\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Scotius","CreatedById":57622,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-03T20:21:43Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nNow that\u0027s pulse drive i don\u0027t mind seeing in action \u003Cspan\u003E\u003Cimg alt=\u0022:)\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_smiley.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:)\u0022\u003E Less raw power than Orion, but also fewer technical headaches - most of all, no nukes onboard \u003Cimg alt=\u0022:cool:\u0022 data-emoticon=\u0022\u0022 src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_cool.gif\u0022 title=\u0022:cool:\u0022\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u003Cspan\u003EAlso... LIKES ARE BACK!!! Finally!\u003C/span\u003E\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Nuke","CreatedById":10883,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-03T21:11:53Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nit would likely need a nuclear reactor on board if you plan on going to the outer solar system with it. solar is fine for a mars mission though. wonder if this thing would fit into a starship.\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Shpaget","CreatedById":45577,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-03T21:21:31Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo, what\u0027s the power source to trigger the fusion?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"farmerben","CreatedById":190194,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-04T00:28:07Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223681335\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188650\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221570137691\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002245577\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Shpaget\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n3 hours ago, Shpaget said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo, what\u0027s the power source to trigger the fusion?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027ve got some ideas on that, but nobody is commenting on them.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Ciframe allowfullscreen=\u0022\u0022 data-controller=\u0022core.front.core.autosizeiframe\u0022 data-embedauthorid=\u0022190194\u0022 data-embedcontent=\u0022\u0022 data-embedid=\u0022embed1655989416\u0022 scrolling=\u0022no\u0022 src=\u0022https://forum.kerbalspaceprogram.com/index.php?/topic/188579-fission-fusion-antimatter-ion-drive/\u0026amp;do=embed\u0022 style=\u0022height:209px;max-width:502px;\u0022\u003E\u003C/iframe\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\n\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nOne thing many people get wrong about any pulse drive system like the Orion, is that we want the maximum possible mass to take the shock, and the minimum possible mass protected by shock absorbers.\u00A0\u00A0\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"kerbiloid","CreatedById":129408,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-04T05:13:52Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223681405\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188650\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221570148887\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u0022190194\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022farmerben\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n4 hours ago, farmerben said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nI\u0027ve got some ideas on that, but nobody is commenting on them.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nCommenting: looked close to my suggestion of optionally-antimatter-enforced Orion\u002BDaedalus hybride engine, lol, so I didn\u0027t.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Nuke","CreatedById":10883,"CreatedDateTime":"2019-10-04T06:47:15Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentapp=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentclass=\u0022forums_Topic\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentcommentid=\u00223681335\u0022 data-ipsquote-contentid=\u0022188650\u0022 data-ipsquote-contenttype=\u0022forums\u0022 data-ipsquote-timestamp=\u00221570137691\u0022 data-ipsquote-userid=\u002245577\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Shpaget\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_citation\u0022\u003E\n9 hours ago, Shpaget said:\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003Cdiv class=\u0022ipsQuote_contents\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nSo, what\u0027s the power source to trigger the fusion?\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003C/div\u003E\n\u003C/blockquote\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\nthere was a reference to a capacitor bank in the paper, i presume you are going to charge it with solar, \u003Cabbr title=\u0022Radio-isotope Thermo-electric Generator (a.k.a. Mars rover heating device)\u0022\u003Ertg\u003C/abbr\u003E, or some kind of fission reactor. looked like they were going to use some kind of inductive compression.\n\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222019-10-04T07:14:33Z\u0022 title=\u002210/04/2019 07:14  AM\u0022 data-short=\u00224 yr\u0022\u003EOctober 4, 2019\u003C/time\u003E by Nuke\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"}]}